 on national, state, and local news, other citizens struggle to do the same. Since not all people have the time or inclination to devote substantial energy to politics, certain forms of participation exacerbate existing inequalities. Democracy for Busy People takes up the very real challenge of how to build a democracy that empowers people with limited time for politics. While many plans for democratic renewal emphasize demanding forms of political participation and daunting ideals of democratic citizenship, political theorist Kevin J. Elliott proposes a fundamentally different approach. He focuses instead on making democratic citizenship undemanding so that even busy people can be politically included. This approach emphasizes the core institutions of electoral democracy, such as political parties, against deliberative reforms and sortition. Timely and action-focused, Democracy for Busy People is necessary reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmericansxPolitical activityxSocial aspects. 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aElectionsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEquality. 0aPolitical participationxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTime managementxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226826318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226826318/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles